qas.question: Which branches of the national military does the U.S. president command?
Whose approval is required for the president's appointees to take office?
What is a Congressional means of removing presidential appointees?
What term can characterize the status of bodies like the War Claims Commission and the Interstate Commerce Commission?
Which of the three branches has the duty of Commander and Chief?
Who has the authority to make treaties?
What is it called when congress terminates an appointment of the President?
Who has over-sight of the Federal Trade Commission?
In whom is Congressional power vested?
What does the Vice President become Commander in Chief of?
By the words it uses, what does the Constitution require the President to do regarding laws?
Laws are made by the President and approved by which body?
Who may the President restrict through impeachment?

context: <a4_0>Executive<a4_0/> power is vested, with exceptions and qualifications, in <a5_0>the <b8_0>President<b8_0/><a5_0/>. By law (Section 2.) the president becomes the Commander in Chief of <b9_0>the <a0_0>Army and Navy<b9_0/><a0_0/>, Militia of several states when called into service, has power to make treaties and appointments to office "with the Advice and Consent of the <a1_0>Senate<a1_0/>," receive Ambassadors and Public Ministers, and "take care that the laws be faithfully executed" (Section 3.) By using these words, the Constitution does not require the president to personally <b10_0>enforce<b10_0/> the law; rather, officers subordinate to the president may perform such duties. The Constitution empowers the president to ensure the faithful execution of the laws made by <a7_0><b11_0>Congress<b11_0/><a7_0/> and approved by the President. <b12_0>Congress<b12_0/> may itself terminate such appointments, by <a2_0><a6_0>impeachment<a6_0/><a2_0/>, and restrict the president. Bodies such as the War Claims Commission, the Interstate Commerce Commission and the Federal Trade Commission—all <a3_0>quasi-judicial<a3_0/>—often have direct Congressional oversight.
